Appendix: Review Form
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D

EACL 2009: 12th Conference of the European Chapter of the=20
     =09   Association for Computational Linguistics

Review Form
-----------

Please evaluate the submission according to the criteria below.

Appropriateness
---------------

Does the paper fit in EACL 2009?

(EACL 2009 invites papers on all aspects of computational=20
linguistics, theoretical and empirical, linguistic and=20
computational, fundamental and applied; see the=20
Call for Papers.)

5 =3D Appropriate for EACL 2009. (<i>most submissions</i>)
4 =3D Linguistics or computer science but not typical EACL material.
3 =3D Possibly relevant to the audience but not really EACL material.
2 =3D Only marginally relevant.
1 =3D Inappropriate.

Clarity
-------

For the reasonably well-prepared reader, is it clear what was
done and why? Is the paper well-written and well-structured?
Does the English or the mathematics need cleaning up? Would=20
the explanation benefit from more examples or pictures?

Is there sufficient detail for an expert to validate the work,
e.g., by replicating experiments or filling in theoretical steps?

(Take into account whether any obscurity or minor English errors
could be fixed with relatively little effort, or whether the=20
paper requires more work than is likely to be carried out in the
few weeks available.)

5 =3D Admirably clear.
4 =3D Understandable by most readers.
3 =3D Mostly understandable to me with some effort.
2 =3D Important questions were hard to resolve even with effort.
1 =3D Much of the paper is confusing.

Soundness/Correctness
---------------------

First, is the general approach sound and well-chosen given the
purpose of the paper? Secondly, can one trust the claims of the=20
paper -- are they supported by proper linguistic analysis,=20
experiments, (other) empirical results, proofs, or other=20
argumentation?

(Note that the kind of support required will be different for=20
different types of papers, theoretical or empirical, linguistic
or computational, fundamental or applied. Please try to assess=20
whether the justification offered is adequate given the goals=20
of the paper.)

5 =3D The approach is very apt, and the claims are convincingly=20
    supported.
4 =3D Generally solid work, though I have a few suggestions about
    how to strengthen the approach or its justification.
3 =3D Fairly reasonable work. The approach is not bad, and at=20
    least the main claims are probably correct, but I am not
    entirely ready to accept them (based on the material in
    the paper).
2 =3D Troublesome. There are some ideas worth salvaging here,
    but the work should really have been done or evaluated
    differently, or justified better.
1 =3D Fatally flawed.

Meaningful Comparison
---------------------

Does the author make clear where the problems and methods sit
with respect to existing literature? Are the references
adequate? Are the new contributions meaningfully compared to
the state of the art in the area, e.g., in terms of=20
experimental results, linguistic coverage, or theoretical=20
properties?

5 =3D Precise and complete comparison with related work. Good
    job given the space constraints.
4 =3D Mostly solid bibliography and comparison, but I have some
    suggestions.
3 =3D Bibliography and comparison are somewhat helpful, but it
    could be hard for a reader to determine exactly how this
    work relates to previous work.
2 =3D Only partial awareness and understanding of related work,
    or a flawed comparison to the state of the art.
1 =3D Little awareness of related work, or lacks necessary=20
    comparison.

Originality/Innovativeness
--------------------------

How original is the approach? Does the paper break new ground in
topic, methodology, or content? How exciting and innovative is=20
the research it describes?

(Note that a paper can score high for originality even if the
benefit of the approach is not yet fully justified.)

5 =3D Surprising: Noteworthy new problem, theory, methodology, or
    insight.
4 =3D Creative: Relatively few people in our community would have=20
    put these ideas together.
3 =3D Somewhat conventional: A number of people could have come up
    with this if they thought about it for a while.
2 =3D Rather boring: Obvious, or a minor modification on a familiar
    theme.
1 =3D Significant portions have actually been done before or done
    better.

Impact of Ideas or Results
--------------------------

How significant is the work described? If the ideas are novel,=20
will they also be useful or inspirational? If the claims and=20
results are sound, are they also important?

5 =3D Will affect the field by altering other people's choice of
    research topics or basic approach.
4 =3D Some of the ideas or results will substantially help other
    people's ongoing research.
3 =3D Interesting but not too influential. The work will be cited,
    but mainly for comparison or as a source of minor=20
    contributions.
2 =3D Marginally interesting. May or may not be cited.
1 =3D Will have no impact on the field.

Recommendation
--------------

There are many good submissions competing for a place at EACL=20
2009. How important is it to feature this one? Will people=20
learn a lot by reading this paper or seeing it presented at
the conference?

In deciding your ultimate recommendation, please think over=20
all your scores above. But remember that no paper is perfect,
and remember that we want a conference full of interesting,
diverse and timely work. If a paper has some weaknesses, but
you really got a lot out of it, feel free to fight for it. If
a paper is solid but you could live without it, let us know
that you're ambivalent. Remember also that the author has a=20
few weeks to address reviewer comments before the=20
camera-ready deadline.

Should the paper be accepted or rejected?

5 =3D Exciting: I'd fight to get it accepted.
4 =3D Worthy: I would like to see it accepted.
3 =3D Borderline: I'm ambivalent about this one.
2 =3D Mediocre: I'd rather not see it in the conference.
1 =3D Poor: I'd fight to have it rejected.

Reviewer confidence
-------------------

5 =3D Positive that my evaluation is correct. I read the paper
    very carefully and am very familiar with related work.
4 =3D Quite sure. I tried to check the important points=20
    carefully, and checked for uncited prior work. It's=20
    unlikely, though conceivable, that I missed something
    that should affect my ratings.
3 =3D Pretty sure, but there's a chance I missed something.
    Although I have a good feel for this area in general, I
    did not carefully check the paper's details, e.g., math,
    linguistic data, experimental design, novelty.
2 =3D Willing to defend evaluation, but it is fairly likely=20
    that I missed some details, didn't understand some=20
    central points, or can't be sure about the novelty of
    the work.
1 =3D Not my area, or paper is very hard to understand. My
    evaluation is just an educated guess.

Mode of Presentation
---------------------------------

We would like your opinion as to whether the paper is best=20
presented as a talk or as a poster.  Your decision should=20
be based on whether you believe the best way to present=20
the work is via a conversation in a small group, or via a=20
monologue. For example, if a paper argues in favor of a=20
general research agenda, and this agenda can be understood
without understanding every single detail, then one could=20
argue that the paper is best presented as a talk/monologue. =20
By contrast, if to appreciate the main point of the paper=20
one must understand fully all its technical details, which=20
in turn you view as hard to get across in a 20 minute talk,=20
then the paper may be construed to be more suitably
presented as a poster/via conversation in small groups.
   =20
Please give us your opinion about what the mode of=20
presentation should be for this paper:
   =20
(Note that this is not a question about the quality of the=20
work, so a low score here does not imply a low overall=20
recommendation.)
   =20
3 =3D This work would be best presented as a poster.
2 =3D This work could be presented equally well as a talk or=20
    as a poster.
1 =3D This work would be best presented as a talk.

Impact on Related Fields
------------------------
   =20
Would this paper be of interest to communities from related=20
fields, and if so, which one?=20

(Note that this is not a question about the quality of the=20
work, so a low score here does not imply a low overall=20
recommendation.)
   =20
3 =3D This paper is equally relevant to a related field as it=20
    is to CL
2 =3D This paper is somewhat relevant to a related field=20
1 =3D This paper is only relevant to CL.
   =20
If your answer is "2" or "3" then please indicate the=20
field(s) you think this paper is relevant to:

_ Linguistics (including phonetics)
_ Computer Science
_ Cognitive science (including psychology)
_ Statistics (including machine learning)
_ Other. Please specify: ................

Detailed Comments
-----------------

Please supply detailed comments to back up your rankings.=20
These comments will be forwarded to the authors of the
paper. The comments will help the committee decide the
outcome of the paper, and will help justify this decision
for the authors. Moreover, if the paper is accepted, the
comments should guide the authors in making revisions for=20
a final manuscript. Hence, the more detailed you make your=20
comments, the more useful your review will be -- both for
the committee and for the authors.

Enter comments here:

...

Confidential Comments for Committee
-----------------------------------

You may wish to withhold some comments from the authors,=20
and include them solely for the committee's internal use.
For example, you may want to express a very strong=20
(negative) opinion on the paper, which might offend the
authors in some way. Or, perhaps, you wish to write=20
something which would expose your identity to the authors.
If you wish to share comments of this nature with the=20
committee, this is the place to put them.

...

